	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Dwedit wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I actually didn't mean that rhetorically, but did B&amp;W TVs made after Color became standard start to filter out the color parts of the signal to make the black &amp; white portion look better?</div>I'm about 90% certain they didn't. I've never seen a monochrome RS170 set with a CRT bigger than 12&quot;, and all of the larger ones were real monitors that used the higher bandwidth available (so wouldn't have a chroma killer). All of the rest I've seen were small portable ones, and once they excluded color display for cost or weight, and lacked RCA input, and the screen was so tiny (3-6&quot;) that 1- the electron beam size was comparable to the chroma dot size, so dot crawl wasn't terribly visible, 2- in case of cost savings, the only cheap chroma killer would be rather blurry and 3- NTSC OTA demodulation already is noisy and bandlimited enough that most chroma dots are drowned out.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
